<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color cyan
May 15 - July 15, 2019
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\color blue
Reducing the flexing of the arms of LISA - a space based Gravitational Wave
 detector
\color inherit

\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset


\size small
Dr.
 Rajesh Nayak, IISER Kolkata
\series default
\size default

\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset

Laser Interferometer Space Antenna (LISA) will be a spaced based gravitational
 wave detector with an array of three spacecrafts in heliocentric orbit.
 I developed a 3-body model to reduce the flexing in the arms of LISA due
 to the breathing modes.
 This project helped me develop computational skills, especially in using
 Python notebooks and theoretical concepts like perturbation theory and
 celestial dynamics.
 The project ended with me writing a Python code that could simulate the
 flexing in the arms of LISA over its observing run.
\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color cyan
Dec.
 08 - Dec.
 25, 2018
\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="left" valignment="top" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\series bold
\color blue
Deriving Geodesic equations for different types of metrics
\series default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset


\series bold
\size small
Dr.
 Naresh Dadhich, IUCAA Pune
\series default
\size default

\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset

A short reading project of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\series bold
Curved Space, curved Time, and curved Space-Time in Schwarzschild geodetic
 geometry (
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "arxiv:1812.03259"
target "https://arxiv.org/abs/1812.03259"
literal "false"

\end_inset

)
\series default
.
 I derived and calculated all the geodesic equations for different types
 of metrics associated with Schwarzschild geometry, considering space and
 time curvatures separately.
 The geodesic equations can then be used to calculate the deflections due
 to 1 solar mass object and it turned out to be exactly half of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

curved spacetime (1.75arcsec)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

curved space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

curved time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 metrics.
\begin_inset Newline linebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
